    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan amortization table and i'm confused. i've been making the same monthly payment for a year now but the principal balance is barely moving. why is the balance decreasing so slowly even though i'm paying the same amount every month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common feeling, but it is actually a classic example of how interest works in a way that feels like a slow, grinding process. When you first start paying off a loan, a significant portion of your monthly payment goes toward the interest that has already accrued on the principal balance.\n\nThink of it like a small, persistent force of nature: the interest is like a tiny, invisible goblin that lives inside your loan account. This goblin eats up a chunk of your payment every single month, leaving very little for the actual principal. As long as the balance is high, the goblin gets bigger and eats more of your payment, making the principal shrink incredibly slowly.\n\nHowever, the good news is that this goblin is not immortal; it is a creature that gets weaker and weaker as you pay it down. Once you've paid off the first few years, the goblin's appetite diminishes, and suddenly, more of your payment goes straight to shrinking the principal. The slow start is just the goblin getting used to its new, larger home.\n\nSo, don't worry about the slow progress right now; you are simply in the early stages of a long battle against the goblin. Once the balance drops",
      "source": "target",
