      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, paying extra directly toward the principal is the most effective way to accelerate your payoff, and it fundamentally changes the math by reducing the \"goblin's\" food supply immediately.\n\nWhen you make an extra payment, you are essentially forcing a larger portion of your fixed monthly payment to go straight to the principal before the interest calculation even happens. This reduces the outstanding balance for the very next month's interest calculation, meaning you pay less interest in that month compared to if you had only paid the minimum.\n\nHere is how the math changes in the long run:\n\n1.  **Immediate Balance Reduction:** Your principal balance drops by the amount of your extra payment plus the interest that would have been accrued on that extra amount (though usually, extra payments are applied directly to principal first).\n2.  **Lower Future Interest:** Because your balance is lower for the next month, the interest calculation ($Balance \\times Rate / 12$) yields a smaller number.\n3.  **Accelerated Principal Growth:** Since your total monthly payment is fixed, a smaller interest bill means a larger chunk of that payment goes to the principal. This creates a positive feedback loop where your principal reduction grows faster every month until the loan is paid off",
